<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n53051b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53051b">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53051b"> 51(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> anthropos / aner <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53051b"><li>FW 318.04f </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/lexma.htm#n53051b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/l39ma.htm#n53051b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53051b">MS BL 47479-124v</ms> </li><li>JJA 54:202 <a name="mad5" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mad5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ma/mad5.htm#n53051b">Draft: II.3&sect;1.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">L&apos;allemand a deux noms de l&apos;&laquo;homme&raquo; : l&apos;un d&eacute;signe le &laquo;m&acirc;le&raquo;, l&apos;individu capable de porter les armes, l&apos;autre est le nom g&eacute;n&eacute;rique de l&apos;esp&egrave;ce humaine : <i>mann</i> et <i>mensch</i> ; de m&ecirc;me le n&eacute;erlandais. Le second de ces noms est un d&eacute;riv&eacute; du premier. Ni en fran&ccedil;ais ni en anglais, on n&apos;observe rien de pareil : <i>homme</i> et <i>man</i> servent &agrave; la fois pour l&apos;une et pour l&apos;autre notions. L&apos;&eacute;tat de choses allemand concorde avec celui de la plupart des anciennes langues indo-europ&eacute;ennes: le sanskrit oppose <i>m&aacute;nu<font color="green">[sdot]</font>a<font color="green">[hdot]</font></i> &agrave; <i>vir&aacute;<font color="green">[hdot]</font></i> et &agrave; <i>na</i> (accusatif <i>n&aacute;ram</i>), le grec <mark><i>&aacute;nthropos</i></mark> (dont l&apos;&eacute;tymologie est obscure) &agrave; <mark><i>an<font color="green">[e]</font>r</i></mark>, l&apos;arm&eacute;nien <i>mard</i> (dont le sens premier est &laquo;mortel&raquo;) &agrave; <i>ayr</i> (qui r&eacute;pond &agrave; grec <i>an<font color="green">[e]</font>r</i>), le lituanien <i>&zcaron;mu~</i> et <i>zmog&ugrave;s</i> &agrave; <i>v&yacute;ras</i>, le slave <i>cloveku</i> &agrave; <i>mo&zcaron;i</i>, le gotique <i>guma</i> &agrave; <i>wair</i>, l&apos;irlandais <i>duine</i> &agrave; <i>fer</i>, le latin enfin <i>homo</i> &agrave; <i>uir</i>. <br><font color="green">[German has two names for &ldquo;man&rdquo;: one refers to the &ldquo;male&rdquo;, the individual able to bear arms, the other is the generic name of the human species: mann and mensch; similar in Dutch. The second of these names is a derivative of the first. Neither French nor English observe anything like it: man and man serve both for one and the other. The German words are consistent with most of the old Indo-European languages: Sanskrit opposes <i>m&aacute;nu[sdot]</font>a<font color="green">[hdot]</font></i> to <i>vir&aacute;<font color="green">[hdot]</font></i> and to na (accusatif n&aacute;ram), the Greek &aacute;nthropos (whose etymology is obscure) to aner, the Armenian mard (whose prime meaning is &ldquo;mortal&rdquo;) to ayr (which answers to Greek aner), the Lithuanian &zcaron;mu and zmog&ugrave;s to v&yacute;ras, Slavic cloveku to mo&zcaron;i, Gothic guma to wair, Irish <i>duine</i> to <i>fer</i, Latin finally <i>hom&omacr;</i> to <i>uir</i>.] <small> Antoine Meillet, &ldquo;Le nom d'homme&rdquo; <a name="LNDH" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LNDH"><cite title="source">Linguistique historique et linguistique g&eacute;n&eacute;rale</cite></a> (1921) 272</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Greek <i>anthropos</i>: man, human being; <i>aner</i>: man, male. </mm> </dd></dl>
